TY  - JOUR
T1  - Do CEOS Encounter Within-Tenure Settling Up? A Multiperiod Perspective on Executive Pay and Dismissal
AU  - Wowak, Adam J.
AU  - Hambrick, Donald C.
AU  - Henderson, Andrew D.
Y1  - 2011/08/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.64869961
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.64869961
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 719
EP  - 739
VL  - 54
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We consider a central puzzle surrounding CEO accountability: What explains the payoffs and penalties that CEOs receive? Invoking Fama's concept of ?settling up,? we examine how a CEO's entire performance record and history of prior over- or underpayment affect current pay and the odds of dismissal. We find that some parts of a CEO's historical track record work to remedy prior over- or underpayment, whereas other aspects result in greater imbalances, as rich CEOs get richer while poorer ones get poorer. History matters when boards reward or punish their CEOs, but such reckoning is relatively complex.
AB  - We consider a central puzzle surrounding CEO accountability: What explains the payoffs and penalties that CEOs receive? Invoking Fama's concept of ?settling up,? we examine how a CEO's entire performance record and history of prior over- or underpayment affect current pay and the odds of dismissal. We find that some parts of a CEO's historical track record work to remedy prior over- or underpayment, whereas other aspects result in greater imbalances, as rich CEOs get richer while poorer ones get poorer. History matters when boards reward or punish their CEOs, but such reckoning is relatively complex.
